Independent Presidential candidate Joseph Nyagah has told President Uhuru Kenyatta to intervene in the Middle East dispute piting Qatar against Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates.He said the feud is disastrous.Nyagah was until last month Uhuru&rsquo;s advisor on regional matters. He said Kenya has over the years been instrumental in reconciling warring countries and should step in to help Qatar.Nyagah resigned to join a list of eight presidential candidates who will be seeking to unseat Uhuru and DP William Ruto in the August 8 election.&ldquo;I call upon our country to help in reconciling our friends in the Middle East to ensure our brothers in Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, UAE and Egypt resolve their differences,&rdquo; Nyagah said in a statement.&ldquo;Kenya has over the years been involved in helping reconcile groups and countries in conflicts within our region and beyond. This is a contribution that the world has come to know us for.&rdquo;Nyagah warned that the conflict could turn ugly and disastrous within the Middle East and in Africa if left unattended.Saudi Arabia, Egypt, UAE and Bahrain have cut ties, especially transport links, with Qatar, accusing it of supporting Islamists.Qatari nationals have been served with notice to leave neighbouring countries as the diplomatic sanctions deepen. Those countries also banned their citizens from entering Qatar.